<subsection xml:id="subsec-application-of-linear-simultaneous-equations-in-real-life">
    <title>Application of Linear Simultaneous Equations in Real Life</title>
    <p>
        Simultaneous equations are used in solving word problem questions with unknown variables.
        Algebraic equations are formed from the word problem.
    </p>
    <p>
        One of the real life applications of simultaneous equations in real life is in business to determine costs of items.
    </p>
    <activity>
        <statement>
            <p>
                <term>Materials needed</term>
            </p>
            <p>
                <ul>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Graph paper 
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Ruler and writing materials
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ul>
            </p>
            <p>
                Juma, a vendor in Gikomba market, sells bananas and mangoes. One of his customers, Aisha, bought <m>5</m> mangoes
                 and <m>2</m> bananas at a cost of <m>Ksh.\, 300.</m> Another customer, Kinara, bought <m>3</m> mangoes and <m>4</m> 
                 bananas for <m>Ksh. \, 240.</m> Find the price of a mango and a banana.
            </p>
            <p>
               <term>Instructions</term> 
            </p>
            <ol>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Form two simultaneous equations from the information above. Use <m>Ksh.\, m</m> as the cost of a mango 
                        and <m>Ksh.\, b</m> as the cost of a banana.  
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Create two tables of value for the coordinates of the two simultaneous equations.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Construct the two lines for the two equations in your graph paper.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Locate the point where the two lines intersect on their graph and write down the coordinates.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        What is the cost of a mango and a banana?
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Discuss your findings with your fellow learners.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
            <p>
                
            </p>
        </statement>
    </activity>
    <example>
    <statement>
        <p>
            Mara and Abdi went to the shop to buy books and pens. Mara bought two books and one 
            pen at a cost of <m>120</m> shillings. Abdi bought two books and two pens at a cost of 
            <m>140</m> shillings. Find the cost of a book and a pen.
            Use <m>x</m> to represent the cost of a book and use <m>y</m> to represent the cost of a pen.
        </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
        <p>
            Cost of a book: <m>x</m>
        </p>
        <p>
            Cost of a pen: <m>y</m>
        </p>
        <p>
            Amount of money Mara spent on buying <m>2</m> books is: <m>2 \times x = 2x</m>
        </p>
        <p>
            The cost of buying <m>1</m> pen is: <m>1 \times y = y</m>
        </p>
        <p>
            The total cost of buying <m>2</m> books and <m>1</m> pen is: 
            <me>
                2x + y = 120
            </me>   
        </p>
         <p>
            Amount of money Abdi spent on buying <m>2</m> books is: <m>2 \times x = 2x</m>
        </p>
        <p>
            The cost of buying <m>2</m> pens is: <m>2 \times y = 2y</m>
        </p>
        <p>
            The sum of buying <m>2</m> books and <m>2</m> pens is: 
            <me>
                2x + 2y = 140
            </me>   
        </p>
        <p>
            The two simultaneous equations formed are:
            <me>
                2x + y = 120.
            </me>
            <me>
                2x + 2y = 140.
            </me>      
        </p>
        <p>
            Form two tables from the two simultaneous equations
        </p>
        <figure xml:id="equations-2">
            <caption>Simultaneous_equation</caption>
            <sidebyside widths="50% 50%">
               <tabular>
                <row>
                    <cell><m> 2x + y = 120</m></cell>
                </row>
            </tabular>
            <tabular>
                <row>
                    <cell><m> 2x + 2y = 140.</m></cell>
                </row>
            </tabular> 
            </sidebyside>   
        </figure>
        <figure xml:id="table-2">
            <caption>Table</caption>
            <sidebyside widths="50% 50%">
            <tabular valign="top" top="minor" bottom="minor" left="minor" right="minor"> 
                <row halign="center">
                    <cell><m>x</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>0</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>20</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>30</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>40</m></cell>
                </row>

                <row halign="center">
                    <cell><m>y</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>120</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>80</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>60</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>40</m></cell>
                </row>
            </tabular>

            <tabular valign="top" top="minor" bottom="minor" left="minor" right="minor"> 
                <row halign="center">
                    <cell><m>x</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>0</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>20</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>30</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>40</m></cell>
                </row>

                <row halign="center">
                    <cell><m>y</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>70</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>50</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>40</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>30</m></cell>
                </row>
            </tabular>
                
            </sidebyside>
        </figure>

        <p>
            Construct the two lines for the equations in your graph as shown below.
        </p>
        <figure>
            <caption>Line Graph</caption>
            <interactive xml:id="geogebra-linear-graph2" platform="geogebra" width="90%" aspect="4:3">
            <slate xml:id="linear-graph2" surface="geogebra" material="srya7mbq" aspect="4:3">
                enableShiftDragZoom(true);
                showResetIcon(false);
            </slate>
            </interactive>
        </figure>

        <p>
            The solution for the two simultaneous equations is the coordinates of the intersection of the two lines. 
        </p>
        <p>
            <m>x = 50</m> and <m>y = 20.</m>
        </p>
        <p>
            Therefore:
        </p>
        <p>
            Cost of a book is <m>50.</m>
        </p>
        <p>
            Cost of a pen is <m> 20.</m>
        </p>

    </solution>
        
    </example>
    
    
</subsection>